Hypothesis tips and tricks

Hypothesis is a great tool and I have found that it works well in this course. Some people find it a little confusing to use so here is a short tutorial to help you in using it.

Before you start

  • First, you should make sure you are using the Chrome browser since it works best there. It should also work in Firefox and Safari but I have found that Chrome is easiest and this tutorial shows you how to use it in Chrome. Get Chrome here if you dont already use it.
  • Next go to Hypothes.is and sign up for an account, and download and install the extension for Chrome. It is free to sign up and they do not collect data on you.
  • Finally make sure you have joined the Ethics@PCT-SP-2021 group. There is a link in the page that you can find in the first checklist.

Basic use

  • I find it helpful to put an icon in the toolbar of Chrome. Do that by first clicking on the jigsaw puzzle piece here:

  • That opens up a window. Click the push pin icon to pin the hypothesis icon to your toolbar. Note that when it is not active it is gray in color.

  • You will want to activate it by clicking on the icon. It will turn black and show you the number of annotations on the current page. That is the total number of notes made by all groups so that number will be higher than what youll see.

  • The arrow on the left opens and closes the annotation window.

  • If you are not logged in, youll see this instead of a person icon. Click here to login.

  • To add an annotation just highlight some text and you should see the box below it. Highlight just adds a highlight with no note, while annotate adds a note. The side bar will open up when you click on either.

  • To hide other peoples annotations so you can read and take notes without the visual clutter, click the eyeball icon.

  • After you select annotate the side bar opens up and you can write your note. Be sure you are writing it in the Ethics @ PCT-SP-2021 group. You can change groups by clicking on the arrow on top.

Click Post to Ethics @ PCT SP-2021 on the bottom to post.

Thats pretty much it!

Some more tricks

  • If you end up using Hypothes.is for more classes or research projects, you can organize your notes by adding keywords or tags. To add a tag, just type a word or a phrase and then hit enter. Then when you go to your Hypothes.is profile page you can look up notes by their tags.

Clicking on this arrow in the corner is how you can get to your Hypothes.is profile page. Click your name to go there.

Here is mine. You can click on the Ethics 2021 group to see everyones posts. Note that your post count doesnt include your replies. Not to worry though I have another way to see those and they do count.

Here is the group page.

Back in Hypothes.is itself, the lower icon in the Hypothes.is tool is for a page note, that is not attached to a highlight and is useful for adding a note to things like videos.

And finally you can create your own private groups for use in other classes. Clicking here brings you to a new screen in which you can pick a name for your group. You can access it in your profile. But do make sure that you post all things for this class into the Ethics 2021 group!
